\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces HCCP at a glance. \textbf  {(a)} Pipeline: data $\to $ aggregator $(\hat  {p}, \hat  {\sigma })$ $\to $ Mondrian $(y \times \hat  {\sigma }\text  {-bin})$ partition with $K = \hat  K(c_{\mathrm  {outer}})$ from nested chrom-LOO $\to $ per-cell quantile $\hat  {q}_{k,b}$ $\to $ prediction set $\mathcal  {C}_\alpha (x)$. The score $s(x,y) = |y - \hat  {p}(x)| / (\hat  {\sigma }(x) + \epsilon )$ scales the decision radius by local uncertainty; per-cell calibration restores (i) class-conditional (T2) and (ii) bin-conditional (T3) coverage, while remaining compatible with \citet  {barber2020limits}'s pointwise impossibility. \textbf  {(b)} Pareto plot on (Cov$|Y{=}1$, $\hat  {\sigma }$-bin gap) using Tab.\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:h2h} bootstrap means ($B = 200$ chrom-resamples). HCCP is the only method in the ideal corner (cov $\geq 0.85$, gap $\leq 0.20$) on both Mendelian and Complex; B1 split CP, B2 $\hat  {\sigma }$-Mondrian, and B3 class-Mondrian each fail at least one axis at $\pi _{+} = 0.10$.}}{2}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:concept}{{1}{2}{HCCP at a glance. \textbf {(a)} Pipeline: data $\to $ aggregator $(\phat , \shat )$ $\to $ Mondrian $(y \times \shat \text {-bin})$ partition with $K = \hat K(c_{\mathrm {outer}})$ from nested chrom-LOO $\to $ per-cell quantile $\qhat _{k,b}$ $\to $ prediction set $\mathcal {C}_\alpha (x)$. The score $s(x,y) = |y - \phat (x)| / (\shat (x) + \epsilon )$ scales the decision radius by local uncertainty; per-cell calibration restores (i) class-conditional (T2) and (ii) bin-conditional (T3) coverage, while remaining compatible with \citet {barber2020limits}'s pointwise impossibility. \textbf {(b)} Pareto plot on (Cov$|Y{=}1$, $\shat $-bin gap) using Tab.~\ref {tab:h2h} bootstrap means ($B = 200$ chrom-resamples). HCCP is the only method in the ideal corner (cov $\geq 0.85$, gap $\leq 0.20$) on both Mendelian and Complex; B1 split CP, B2 $\shat $-Mondrian, and B3 class-Mondrian each fail at least one axis at $\pi _{+} = 0.10$}{figure.1}{}}
